arXiv:2405.00777v1 Announce Type: new Abstract: We investigate the possibility of using the Short-Baseline Near Detector (SBND) at Fermilab to constrain lepton flavor violating decays of pions and kaons. We study how to leverage SBND-PRISM, the use of the neutrino beam angular spread to mitigate systematic uncertainties, to enhance this analysis. We show that SBND-PRISM can put stringent limits on the flavor violating branching ratios $m{BR}(\pi^+ 	o \mu^+ 
u_e) = 8.9 	imes 10^{-4}$, $m{BR}(K^+ 	o \mu^+ 
u_e) = 3.2 	imes 10^{-3}$, improving previous constraints by factors 9 and 1.25, respectively. We also estimate the SBND-PRISM sensitivity to lepton number violating decays, $m{BR}(\pi^+ 	o \mu^+ \overline{
u}_e)= 2.1 	imes 10^{-3}$ and $m{BR}(K^+ 	o \mu^+ \overline{
u}_e) = 7.4 	imes 10^{-3}$, though not reaching previous BEBC limits. Last, we identify several ways how the SBND collaboration could improve this analysis.
